{"text": " Your Christmas lights almost didn't exist. Let me show you why. So to make white light, you need three colors. Red and green will make yellow. And for all white LED light, you need blue. But this was a big problem because for a long time, we can only make red and green, which make yellow. It took decades longer to make blue because energy. LED light is made when electrons dance. So when you give electrons a push of energy, they jump to an excited state, but they don't want to stay there for long. They fall back down. And that fall releases energy as heat and light. And the height of the fall determines the color emitted. A little drop is less energy, and that makes red a longer wavelength. And a big drop is more energy and makes blue a shorter wavelength. So the challenge was finding a material that could create those higher energy jumps. It took us until the 90s to find that perfect material. Gallium nitrite. And now that we have scientists are getting even better at making super efficient, deep blue LEDs with other materials. If you want more optimistic science and tech stories, follow along.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 1.84, "text": " Your Christmas lights almost didn't exist.", "tokens": [50364, 2260, 5272, 5811, 1920, 994, 380, 2514, 13, 50456], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13545518378688864, "compression_ratio": 1.745819397993311, "no_speech_prob": 0.00967548880726099}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 1.84, "end": 2.64, "text": " Let me show you why.", "tokens": [50456, 961, 385, 855, 291, 983, 13, 50496], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13545518378688864, "compression_ratio": 1.745819397993311, "no_speech_prob": 0.00967548880726099}, {"id": 2, "seek": 0, "start": 2.64, "end": 5.5600000000000005, "text": " So to make white light, you need three colors.", "tokens": [50496, 407, 281, 652, 2418, 1442, 11, 291, 643, 1045, 4577, 13, 50642], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13545518378688864, "compression_rat